[1mDESCRIPTION[0m
       ranger is a console file manager with VI key bindings.

[1mRESOURCES[0m
       This [4mmanual[24m contains instructions on how to use and configure ranger.

       Inside [4mranger[24m, you can press [4m?[24m for a list of key bindings, commands or settings.

       The [4mREADME[24m contains install instructions.

       The file [4mHACKING.md[24m contains guidelines for code modification.

       The directory [4mdoc/configs[24m contains configuration files.  They are usually installed
       to [4m/usr/share/doc/ranger/config[24m and can be obtained with ranger's --copy-config
       option.

       The directory [4mexamples[24m contains reference implementations for ranger plugins,
       sample configuration files and some programs for integrating ranger with other
       software.  They are usually installed to [4m/usr/share/doc/ranger/examples[24m.

       The man page of [1mrifle[22m(1) describes the functions of the file opener

       The section [4mLINKS[24m of this man page contains further resources.

[1mPOSITIONAL ARGUMENTS[0m
       [4mpath[24m [4m...[24m      Each  path  will be opened in a tab and if the path is a file it will
                     be selected.  Omitting this is equivalent to  providing  the  current
                     directory.

[1mOPTIONS[0m
       [1m-d[22m, [1m--debug   [22mActivate  the  debug mode: Whenever an error occurs, ranger will exit
                     and print a full traceback.  The default behavior is to merely  print
                     the  name  of  the  exception  in  the  statusbar/log and try to keep
                     running.

       [1m-c[22m, [1m--clean   [22mActivate the clean mode:   ranger  will  not  access  or  create  any
                     configuration  files  nor  will  it  leave any traces on your system.
                     This is useful when your configuration is broken, when  you  want  to
                     avoid clutter, etc.

       [1m--cachedir[22m=[4mdir[0m
                     Change   the  cache  directory  of  ranger  from  $XDG_CACHE_HOME  or
                     ~/.cache/ranger to "dir".

       [1m-r [4m[22mdir[24m, [1m--confdir[22m=[4mdir[0m
                     Change the configuration directory of ranger from $XDG_CONFIG_HOME or
                     ~/.config/ranger to "dir".

       [1m--datadir[22m=[4mdir[24m Change  the  data  directory  of  ranger   from   $XDG_DATA_HOME   or
                     ~/.local/share/ranger to "dir".

       [1m--copy-config[22m=[4mfile[0m
                     Create  copies  of  the  default  configuration  files  in your local
                     configuration directory.  Existing  ones  will  not  be  overwritten.
                     Possible values: [4mall[24m, [4mcommands[24m, [4mcommands_full[24m, [4mrc[24m, [4mrifle[24m, [4mscope[24m.

                     Note:  You  may  want  to disable loading of the global configuration
                     files by exporting [4mRANGER_LOAD_DEFAULT_RC=FALSE[24m in your  environment.
                     See also: [1mFILES[22m, [1mENVIRONMENT[0m

                     --copy-config=[1mcommands  [22mwill  copy  only a small sample configuration
                     file with a thoroughly commented example.  It is recommended to  keep
                     this  file tidy to avoid getting defunct commands on ranger upgrades.
                     The    full    default    commands.py    can    be    copied     with
                     --copy-config=[1mcommands_full[22m,  but that file will be ignored by ranger
                     and serves only as a reference for making your own commands.

       [1m--choosefile[22m=[4mtargetfile[0m
                     Allows you to pick a file with ranger.  This changes the behavior  so
                     that  when  you  open a file, ranger will exit and write the absolute
                     path of that file into [4mtargetfile[24m.

       [1m--choosefiles[22m=[4mtargetfile[0m
                     Allows you to pick multiple files  with  ranger.   This  changes  the
                     behavior so that when you open a file, ranger will exit and write the
                     absolute  paths  of  all  selected  files into [4mtargetfile[24m, adding one
                     newline after each filename.

       [1m--choosedir[22m=[4mtargetfile[0m
                     Allows you to pick a directory with ranger.  When you exit ranger, it
                     will write the last visited directory into [4mtargetfile[24m.

       [1m--selectfile[22m=[4mtargetfile[0m
                     Open ranger with  [4mtargetfile[24m  selected.  This  is  a  legacy  option,
                     superseded by the behavior for the POSITIONAL ARGUMENTS.

       [1m--show-only-dirs[0m
                     Display  only  the  directories.  May  be  used  in  conjunction with
                     [1m--choosedir[22m=[4mtargetfile[24m.

       [1m--list-unused-keys[0m
                     List common keys which are not bound to any action in  the  "browser"
                     context.   This  list  is  not complete, you can bind any key that is
                     supported by curses: use the key code returned by "getch()".

       [1m--list-tagged-files[22m=[4mtag[0m
                     List all files which are tagged with the given tag.  Note:  Tags  are
                     single characters.  The default tag is "*"

       [1m--profile     [22mPrint statistics of CPU usage on exit.

       [1m--cmd[22m=[4mcommand[24m Execute  the command after the configuration has been read.  Use this
